Some ex-militants in Ondo State on Monday protested non-inclusion in the Federal Government amnesty program despite submitting their arms and ammunition. The ex-militants who carried placards of various inscriptions said they were disappointed that they were yet to be integrated into the programme. The spokesperson to the protesting ex-militants, General Ogalo Ibori, said they have been grievously affected by the many years of neglect since their accepted amnesty. He urged President Muhammadu Buhari to intervene and address their situation by properly integrating them into the society since they don’t want to go back to the creek. The Nation ABUJA (Sundiata Post) - An ex-Niger Delta militant and former member of the Movement for the Emancipation of Niger Delta, 'General' Tamunotonye Kuna (alias Obese), has vowed "never to return to the creeks because violence doesn't pay." He also condemned the activities of the Niger Delta Avengers, describing them as… In "Top Stories" By Ayodeji Alabi Akure - Gov. Oluwarotimi Akeredolu of Ondo State on Monday reiterated his commitment to ensuring  that former militants  in Ilaje and Ese-Odo Local Governments in the state were integrated into the Federal Government Amnesty Programme. Akeredolu stated this during a “ thank you tour’’  to Ilaje, Ese-Odo,… In "News" A group of ex-militants yesterday threatened to resume hostilities in the oil producing areas of Ondo State if the Federal Government did not appoint an indigene of the area into the board of the Niger Delta Development Commission (NDDC). The grouse of the ex-militants in the Eagle Strike Camp in… In "News"